<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<exercise xml:id="reading-question-composition-and-jectivity" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>
    Composition and <q> jectivity </q>
  </title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let <m> f \colon X \to Y </m> and <m> g \colon Y \to Z </m> be maps between sets <m> X </m>, <m> Y </m>, and <m> Z </m>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that if <m> f </m> and <m> g </m> are injective, then so is their composition <m> g \circ f \colon X \to Z </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        Let <m> x_{ 1 } , x_{ 2 } \in X </m>, and suppose that <m> \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 1 } } = \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 2 } } </m>. Then
        
        <md>
          g \of{ f \of{ x_{ 1 } } } = \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 1 } } = \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 2 } } = g \of{ f \of{ x_{ 2 } } }
        </md>,
        
        and so the injectivity of <m> g </m> implies that <m> f \of{ x_{ 1 } } = f \of{ x_{ 2 } } </m>. Moreover, the injectivity of <m> f </m> implies that <m> x_{ 1 } = x_{ 2 } </m>. In summary, we have shown that for all inputs <m> x_{ 1 } , x_{ 2 } \in X </m>, if <m> \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 1 } } = \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 2 } } </m>, then <m> x_{ 1 } = x_{ 2 } </m>; that is, <m> g \circ f </m> is injective.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that if <m> f </m> and <m> g </m> are surjective, then so is their composition <m> g \circ f \colon X \to Z </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        Let <m> z \in Z </m>. Since <m> g </m> is surjective, <m> z = g \of{ y } </m> for some <m> y \in Y </m>. Moreover, since <m> f </m> is surjective, <m> y = f \of{ x } </m> for some <m> x \in X </m>. Thus
        
        <md>
          z = g \of{ y } = g \of{ f \of{ x } } = \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x }
        </md>.
        
        In summary, we have shown that for every output <m> z \in Z </m>, there is some input <m> x \in X </m> so that <m> z = \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x } </m>; that is, <m> g \circ f </m> is surjective.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that if <m> f </m> and <m> g </m> are bijective, then so is their composition <m> g \circ f \colon X \to Z </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since <m> f </m> and <m> g </m> are bijective, they are both injective and surjective. (1) and (2) above not imply that their composition <m> g \circ f </m> is both injective and surjective; that is, <m> g \circ f </m> is bijective.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that if the composition <m> g \circ f \colon X \to Z </m> is injective, then so is <m> f </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <hint>
      <p>
        Prove the desired result by contraposition.
      </p>
    </hint>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m> f </m> is not injective. Then <m> f \of{ x_{ 1 } } = f \of{ x_{ 2 } } </m> for some distinct inputs <m> x_{ 1 } , x_{ 2 } \in X </m>. Note that
        
        <md>
          \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 1 } } = g \of{ f \of{ x_{ 1 } } } = g \of{ f \of{ x_{ 2 } } } = \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 2 } }
        </md>.
        
        Since <m> \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 1 } } = \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x_{ 2 } } </m> but <m> x_{ 1 } \neq x_{ 2 } </m>, <m> g \circ f </m> is not injective.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        In summary, we have shown that if <m> f </m> is not injective, then <m> g \circ f </m> is not injective. The contrapositive of this implication is the desired result: if <m> g \circ f </m> is injective, then so is <m> f </m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that if the composition <m> g \circ f \colon X \to Z </m> is surjective, then so is <m> g </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <hint>
      <p>
        Prove the desired result by contraposition.
      </p>
    </hint>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m> g </m> is not surjective. Then there is some <m> z \in Z </m> so that <m> z \neq g \of{ y } </m> for all <m> y \in Y </m>. Note that
        
        <md>
          \of{ g \circ f } \of{ x } = g \of{ f \of{ x } } \neq z
        </md>
        
        for all <m> x \in X </m>, and so <m> g \circ f </m> is not surjective.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        In summary, we have shown that if <m> g </m> is not surjective, then <m> g \circ f </m> is not surjective. The contrapositive of this implication is the desired result: if <m> g \circ f </m> is surjective, then so is <m> g </m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>
